Quick Comparison: PageIndex Vectorless vs. Vector DB RAG

PageIndex Vectorless RAG (e.g., via LlamaIndex's PageIndex or Elasticsearch BM25-style indexing):
How it works: Indexes documents at the page/paragraph level using keyword-based retrieval (no embeddings). Matches queries via exact terms, TF-IDF, or BM25 scoring—great for structured data like Excel tables or PDF sections where you need precise, rule-based hits (e.g., "find all rows where Revenue > $10M in Q4").
Pros:
Faster/cheaper setup (no GPU for embeddings; CPU-only).
Better for exact matches in tabular/financial data (e.g., Excel formulas intact).
Lower latency (~50–100ms/query); handles large docs without chunking issues.

Cons:
Poor semantic understanding—misses synonyms (e.g., "synergies" vs. "cost savings").
Scales poorly for fuzzy M&A queries like "assess IP risks in supplier contracts."
In 2026 benchmarks (e.g., RAGAS evals), recall drops 20–30% on unstructured PDFs vs. vectors.

Best for: Simple, high-precision tasks like Excel lookups in sell-side financial normalization.

Vector DB RAG (e.g., FAISS, Pinecone, or Weaviate):
How it works: Chunks docs into vectors (via embeddings like Sentence Transformers or OpenAI's text-embedding-3-large), stores in a vector database for cosine similarity search. Retrieves top-k chunks, then generates with an LLM (e.g., Llama 3.1).
Pros:
Semantic search shines for M&A nuance (e.g., linking "working capital trends" across Excel tabs and PDF footnotes).
Handles mixed data (Excel tables + PDF narratives) with multimodal embeddings.
2026 state: Hybrid modes (vector + keyword reranking) boost accuracy to 85–95% on finance datasets.

Cons:
Higher setup cost (embeddings need ~4–8GB RAM/GPU for indexing 1K docs).
Chunking artifacts can fragment Excel tables; latency ~200–500ms.

Best for: Complex agent reasoning, like a "Synergy Estimator Agent" cross-referencing client-only PDFs.


Which is Best? For your M&A knowledge system (Excel/PDF company data), go with a Hybrid Vector DB RAG as the core—vector for 80% semantic retrieval, vectorless (PageIndex/BM25) for 20% precision reranking. Why? Pure vectorless falls short on the interpretive queries agents need (e.g., "flag tax risks"), while pure vector DB misses exact Excel matches. Hybrids (via LangChain or Haystack) outperform by 25–40% in evals like those from Hugging Face's RAG leaderboard (as of Q1 2026). If your data is 90%+ tabular (e.g., pure financial Excels), lean vectorless to start—it's 3x faster to prototype.
