Core Simulations Used to Finalize Deals
Here's the most common ones, ranked by frequency of use in practice (based on investment banking, private equity, and corporate development workflows):

Sensitivity Analysis (Most Ubiquitous)
What it is: Systematically varies 1–2 key inputs (e.g., revenue growth, EBITDA margins, synergy capture %, purchase multiple, WACC/discount rate) while holding others constant, to see impact on outputs like post-deal EPS, IRR, accretion/dilution, or net debt/EBITDA.
Purpose in finalization: Identifies "breaking points" — e.g., "If synergies are only 60% realized, does the deal still accrete EPS in Year 1?" or "At what purchase price does IRR drop below 20%?"
Typical outputs: Data tables (often 2D sensitivities in Excel), tornado charts, spider diagrams.
Used for: Accretion/dilution testing in strategic M&A; IRR thresholds in PE/LBO deals; negotiating price collars or earn-outs.
Why it finalizes deals: Boards demand to see downside protection; it's quick and transparent.

Scenario Analysis (Base / Best / Worst Case)
What it is: Builds 3–5 coherent "stories" (base case = management plan; upside = aggressive synergies + strong macro; downside = recession, integration slippage, regulatory hurdles).
Purpose in finalization: Tests holistic deal rationale under realistic futures; often includes pro forma combined financials, balance sheet impact, and covenant headroom.
Typical outputs: Full pro forma models under each scenario, with key metrics (e.g., leverage ratio Day 1, free cash flow coverage).
Used for: Assessing integration risk, financing feasibility (e.g., debt capacity in stressed scenarios), and post-closing capital structure.
Why it finalizes deals: Helps set walk-away triggers (e.g., "If worst-case leverage >6x, renegotiate or terminate").

Monte Carlo Simulation (Advanced / Probabilistic – Increasingly Common in 2025–2026)
What it is: Runs thousands of iterations (e.g., 10,000–100,000) where multiple input variables are randomly sampled from probability distributions (e.g., revenue growth ~ Normal(8%, 3% std dev); margin ~ Triangular(min, mode, max); exit multiple ~ Lognormal).
Purpose in finalization: Produces a distribution of outcomes (e.g., IRR histogram, probability of EPS accretion >5%, Value at Risk, or chance of default post-close).
Typical outputs: Probability distributions, confidence intervals (e.g., 80% chance IRR >18%), cumulative distribution functions, tornado plots of variable importance.
Used for: High-uncertainty deals (tech/SaaS with lumpy revenue, carve-outs, cross-border with FX risk), PE portfolio company exits, or when synergies are highly variable.
Why it finalizes deals: Quantifies "tail risks" that deterministic models miss; supports risk-adjusted pricing (e.g., lower bid if P(IRR < hurdle) > 20%); increasingly required by sophisticated boards/PE funds.

Merger Model / Accretion-Dilution Analysis (Core Deal Mechanics Simulation)
What it is: A dynamic pro forma model combining buyer + target financials, layering in purchase accounting (goodwill, asset step-ups), new debt/equity issuance, synergies phasing, and tax effects.
Purpose in finalization: Calculates exact EPS impact Year 1–5, breakeven synergy levels, and balance sheet pro forma.
Typical outputs: Accretion/dilution bridge, sources & uses table, contribution analysis.
Used for: Strategic deals (public company buyers care deeply about EPS dilution); often combined with sensitivities.

Other Supporting Simulations (Less Frequent but Deal-Clinching in Specific Cases)
