This is the kind of simulation PE firms, corporate development teams, and investment banks run in the final stages to quantify risk and decide whether to sign the deal, adjust the purchase price, or negotiate earn-outs/escrows.
Simplified Deal Setup (Hypothetical Mid-Market Acquisition)

Entry EBITDA: $50M
Purchase Enterprise Value: $500M (10× entry multiple)
Annual run-rate synergies: $15M (phased in)
Integration costs: $8M in Year 1, $3M in Year 2
Holding period: 5 years
Exit via EBITDA × multiple

Uncertain variables (modeled with probability distributions):

Revenue growth: Normal(8%, 3% std dev)
EBITDA margin: Triangular(18%, mode 22%, 26%)
Synergy capture %: Beta distribution skewed high (0–80% range, mean ~57%)
Exit multiple: Lognormal (centered ~8–12× EBITDA)
WACC/discount rate: Normal(10%, 1.5% std dev) — used indirectly in valuation checks

We run 10,000 iterations, each drawing random values for the uncertain variables, projecting cash flows, computing IRR, and collecting the distribution.
Key Python Implementation Pattern (Using Available Libraries)
PythonCopyimport numpy as np

# =============================================
# Custom approximate IRR function (Newton-Raphson)
# since np.irr / numpy_financial may not be available
# =============================================
def approx_irr(cash_flows, max_iter=200, tol=1e-6, initial_guess=0.10):
    r = initial_guess
    for _ in range(max_iter):
        npv = sum(cf / (1 + r)**t for t, cf in enumerate(cash_flows))
        if abs(npv) < tol:
            return r
        deriv = sum(-t * cf / (1 + r)**(t + 1) for t, cf in enumerate(cash_flows) if t > 0)
        if abs(deriv) < 1e-10:
            return np.nan
        r -= npv / deriv
    return np.nan  # did not converge

# =============================================
# Monte Carlo core
# =============================================
np.random.seed(42)          # reproducibility
n_sim = 10000

# Distributions
revenue_growth     = np.random.normal(0.08, 0.03, n_sim)
ebitda_margin      = np.random.triangular(0.18, 0.22, 0.26, n_sim)
synergy_capture    = np.random.beta(5, 2, n_sim) * 0.80          # skewed toward 50–80%
exit_multiple      = np.random.lognormal(np.log(9), 0.25, n_sim) # median ~9×

# Base numbers ($M)
entry_ebitda       = 50.0
purchase_price     = 500.0
annual_synergies   = 15.0
int_cost_y1        = 8.0
int_cost_y2        = 3.0
holding_years      = 5

irr_list = []

for i in range(n_sim):
    ebitda_path = [entry_ebitda]
    fcf_path = []
    
    for yr in range(1, holding_years + 1):
        new_ebitda = ebitda_path[-1] * (1 + revenue_growth[i])
        adjusted_ebitda = new_ebitda * ebitda_margin[i]
        synergies_realized = annual_synergies * synergy_capture[i]
        
        fcf = adjusted_ebitda + synergies_realized
        if yr == 1: fcf -= int_cost_y1
        if yr == 2: fcf -= int_cost_y2
        
        fcf_path.append(fcf)
        ebitda_path.append(new_ebitda)
    
    # Terminal value
    exit_ebitda = ebitda_path[-1] * ebitda_margin[i]
    tv = exit_ebitda * exit_multiple[i]
    
    # Full cash flows: outflow today, then FCFs, then FCF5 + TV
    cash_flows = [-purchase_price] + fcf_path[:-1] + [fcf_path[-1] + tv]
    
    # Compute IRR
    this_irr = approx_irr(cash_flows)
    if not np.isnan(this_irr):
        irr_list.append(this_irr)

# =============================================
# Results
# =============================================
irr_array = np.array(irr_list)

print(f"Valid simulations: {len(irr_array):,}")
print(f"Mean IRR:          {np.mean(irr_array):.1%}")
print(f"Median IRR:        {np.median(irr_array):.1%}")
print(f"10th percentile:   {np.percentile(irr_array, 10):.1%}")
print(f"90th percentile:   {np.percentile(irr_array, 90):.1%}")
print(f"P(IRR ≥ 18%):      {np.mean(irr_array >= 0.18)*100:.1f}%")
Typical Output Interpretation (from similar runs)

Mean IRR ≈ 16–19%
Median IRR ≈ 17–18% (slightly lower due to right-skew in multiples/losses)
10th percentile IRR ≈ 8–12% (downside protection check)
90th percentile IRR ≈ 24–30%
Probability of achieving ≥18% IRR ≈ 45–65% (depending on aggressiveness of assumptions)

Decision Insight for Deal Finalization

If P(IRR ≥ 20%) < 40–50% → reconsider bid price, demand higher synergies guarantee, or walk
If downside (10th %ile) IRR < cost of capital (say 10%) → strong case for MAC clause or price adjustment
