How OU Helps with Synergy Matching & Realization
Synergies rarely stay flat forever: cost synergies often peak early (e.g., headcount reductions) then partially erode due to cultural friction, re-hiring, or inflation; revenue synergies may surge from cross-selling but revert as competition responds or customers churn. OU models this mean reversion elegantly.

Modeling Synergy Decay / Fade:
Treat the synergy level (e.g., annual $ cost savings or incremental EBITDA margin) as an OU process:
dS_t = κ (θ - S_t) dt + σ dW_t
κ = speed of reversion (how fast synergies decay toward "normal")
θ = long-term sustainable synergy level (often lower than initial target)
σ = volatility of realization (execution risk, integration surprises)
S_t = synergy value at time t

This captures: high initial realization → gradual pull-back to a realistic equilibrium (e.g., 60–80% of announced synergies often materialize long-term).

Probabilistic Synergy Matching & Valuation:
In Monte Carlo simulations (as in our earlier IRR example), replace deterministic synergy phasing with OU-generated paths.
→ Output: distribution of realized NPV of synergies → compare to premium paid → assess if the deal creates value under realistic fade scenarios.
→ Helps answer: "What's the probability that synergies cover the control premium after reversion?" or "How sensitive is accretion to synergy decay speed?"

Synergy Risk Flags & Scenario Differentiation:
Fit OU parameters from historical post-merger data (e.g., public deals in the sector) or internal pilots.
High κ → fast fade → conservative synergy credit in models.
Low θ → limited long-term value → renegotiate earn-outs or price.

Differentiate cost vs. revenue synergies: cost often reverts faster (κ high) due to one-time cuts; revenue may have slower reversion (κ lower) but higher volatility (σ larger).

