$$dr_t = a(b - r_t) \, dt + \sigma \, dW_t$$

$  a > 0  $: speed of mean reversion (how quickly rates pull back to equilibrium).
$  b  $: long-term mean (equilibrium) interest rate.
$  \sigma > 0  $: volatility of the short rate.
$  dW_t  $: Wiener process (standard Brownian motion).

Key features include mean reversion (rates tend to revert to $  b  $ after shocks) and the possibility of negative rates (a limitation in low-rate environments, addressed by extensions like CIR). It yields closed-form solutions for bond prices, yields, and many derivatives.
