Core Hull-White Model (One-Factor Version)
The short-rate dynamics under the risk-neutral measure are:
$$dr_t = [\theta(t) - a r_t] \, dt + \sigma \, dW_t$$

$  a > 0  $: Constant mean reversion speed (how fast rates revert).
$  \theta(t)  $: Time-dependent function that drives the model to fit the current term structure exactly (derived from observed forward rates).
$  \sigma  $: Constant volatility (in the basic one-factor version).
This is often called the extended Vasicek model because it generalizes Vasicek by making the long-term mean time-varying via $  \theta(t)  $.

Key extension features:

Time-dependent mean reversion level $  \theta(t)  $ → Ensures exact fit to the initial yield curve (zero-coupon bonds, forwards) at t=0, unlike constant-parameter Vasicek or CIR.
In more flexible versions (sometimes called "extended Hull-White"), $  a(t)  $ and/or $  \sigma(t)  $ can also be time-dependent.

Closed-form solutions exist for:

Zero-coupon bond prices $  P(t,T)  $.
Bond options, caps/floors, swaptions (via Jamshidian decomposition or trees).
Affine term structure → Easy calibration and Monte Carlo paths.

