Core Dynamics of the Two-Factor Hull-White Model
The most common formulation (as in Hull & White 1994/2006, Brigo & Mercurio equivalents, and many implementations) represents the short rate $  r(t)  $ as the sum of a deterministic fit component and two mean-reverting stochastic factors:
$$r(t) = \alpha(t) + x(t) + y(t)$$
Where:

$  \alpha(t)  $: Deterministic time-dependent function chosen to exactly fit the initial observed term structure (forward curve) — similar to the one-factor version.
$  x(t)  $: Fast mean-reverting factor (often interpreted as short-term deviations or "transitory" shocks).
$  y(t)  $: Slower mean-reverting factor (captures longer-term or "persistent" level shifts).

The stochastic dynamics (under the risk-neutral measure) are:
$$dx(t) = -a_x x(t) \, dt + \sigma_x \, dW_x(t)$$
$$dy(t) = -a_y y(t) \, dt + \sigma_y \, dW_y(t)$$
With initial conditions $  x(0) = y(0) = 0  $, and correlated Brownian motions:
$$\langle dW_x(t), dW_y(t) \rangle = \rho \, dt \quad (-1 \leq \rho \leq 1)$$
Typical parameter interpretation:

$  a_x > a_y  $ (short-rate factor reverts faster, e.g., months; long-rate factor slower, e.g., years).
$  \sigma_x, \sigma_y  $: Volatilities of each factor.
$  \rho  $: Instantaneous correlation between shocks — controls how factors move together (high positive → parallel shifts dominate; low/negative → twists/humps possible).

The function $  \alpha(t)  $ is derived analytically to match the current yield curve exactly (no-arbitrage condition), incorporating adjustments for the volatilities and correlation:
$$\alpha(t) = f^M(0,t) + \frac{\sigma_x^2}{2 a_x^2} (1 - e^{-a_x t})^2 + \frac{\sigma_y^2}{2 a_y^2} (1 - e^{-a_y t})^2 + \rho \frac{\sigma_x \sigma_y}{a_x a_y} (1 - e^{-a_x t})(1 - e^{-a_y t})$$
(f^M(0,t) is the market instantaneous forward rate at t=0.)
Bond prices, option prices (caps, swaptions), etc., have closed-form or semi-closed-form expressions (affine structure), though more complex than one-factor (involving correlation terms like C(t,T)).
