Task chaining in CrewAI (v0.5+, as of March 2026) refers to the sequential or conditional orchestration of tasks across agents in a "crew," where outputs from one task/agent feed directly into the next. This creates a stateful workflow—like a virtual M&A team passing handoffs (e.g., financial normalization → risk flagging → integration planning)—without manual intervention. It's powered by CrewAI's Task and Crew classes, with optional extensions via LangGraph for complex branching.
In our M&A Orchestrator prototype, chaining turns isolated agents into a cohesive pipeline: e.g., Financial Agent's IRR sim outputs become inputs for Integration Agent's churn modeling. This reduces latency (parallelizable) and boosts accuracy (context propagation via shared memory).
Why Task Chaining Matters for M&A

Efficiency: Automates 70–80% of iterative steps (e.g., diligence → valuation → risks), cutting weeks off deals.
Context Retention: Prevents "amnesia" in LLMs—e.g., ESG flags inform synergy fade in Monte Carlo.
Conditional Logic: Branch on risks (e.g., if cyber score <0.7, escalate to Legal Agent).
Scalability: Handles 10+ agents; integrates with our RAG for grounded chaining.

Core Concepts

Tasks: Atomic units (description + agent + expected_output). Use context to chain: Task(..., context=[prev_task]).
Chaining Types:
Sequential: Linear handoff (default in Crew).
Parallel: Multiple tasks run concurrently (via allow_delegation=True).
Hierarchical/Conditional: Use decomposition or LangGraph for "if-then" (e.g., high HHI → antitrust deep-dive).

State Management: CrewAI's built-in memory (short/long-term); augment with our SQLite audit logs.
Delegation: Agents can "delegate" subtasks (e.g., Financial delegates to Scout for comps).

Implementation Steps

Define Tasks with Context: Link via context param.
Assemble Crew: Pass tasks list; enable verbose=2 for tracing.
Run & Handle Outputs: crew.kickoff(inputs={...}) propagates state.
Advanced: Wrap in LangGraph for graphs (e.g., loops on escalations).

