Want the exact code to add a analyze_peers tool that chains FinanceDatabase → FinanceToolkit → ratios output? Or a sample agent task that uses it? Just say the word.20 sourcesDCF valuation model detailsThe Discounted Cash Flow (DCF) model is one of the most widely used intrinsic valuation methods in finance, especially in M&A, private equity, corporate development, investment banking, and equity research. It estimates a company's (or asset's) fair value by projecting its future free cash flows and discounting them back to present value using an appropriate discount rate that reflects risk and the time value of money.
Core Concept
The value of any asset today equals the present value of all cash it is expected to generate in the future.
Basic DCF Formula (single-period version):
$$\text{DCF Value} = \sum_{t=1}^{n} \frac{\text{FCF}_t}{(1 + r)^t} + \frac{\text{Terminal Value}}{(1 + r)^n}$$
Where:

FCF_t = Free Cash Flow in year t (usually Unlevered Free Cash Flow = FCFF in M&A contexts)
r = Discount rate (most often WACC = Weighted Average Cost of Capital)
n = Length of explicit forecast period (typically 5–10 years)
Terminal Value = Value of all cash flows beyond the explicit forecast period

Two Main Variants Used in M&A

Unlevered DCF (Enterprise Value) — Most common in M&A
Uses Unlevered Free Cash Flow (UFCF / FCFF)
Produces Enterprise Value (EV) → add cash, subtract debt/minority interest/preferred → Equity Value
Independent of capital structure → ideal for comparing companies and acquisition targets

Levered DCF (Equity Value)
Uses Free Cash Flow to Equity (FCFE)
Directly gives Equity Value (share price × shares)
More common in dividend discount models or equity research, less used in M&A


Detailed Step-by-Step Guide to Building a DCF Model (M&A Context)
Step 1: Historical Financials & Normalization (1–3 years back)

Collect audited financial statements (10-K / annual report / data room).
Normalize EBITDA / EBIT:
Remove one-offs (restructuring, legal settlements, non-recurring gains/losses)
Adjust for accounting changes, non-operating income

Calculate historical Unlevered Free Cash Flow:

$$\text{UFCF} = \text{EBIT} \times (1 - \text{Tax Rate}) + \text{D\&A} - \Delta \text{NWC} - \text{Capex}$$

Or more precisely:
EBIT × (1 – Tax Rate) = NOPAT
NOPAT + D&A – ΔNWC – Capex = UFCF


Step 2: Explicit Forecast Period (5–10 years)

Revenue — Driver-based forecast (volume × price, market share × TAM, CAGR based on industry + company guidance)
Margins — Gross, EBITDA, EBIT (trend toward industry average or management target)
Working Capital — Days sales outstanding (DSO), DIO, DPO → projected change in NWC
Capex — Maintenance + growth capex (often % of revenue or depreciation + growth)
Tax Rate — Effective rate → normalized long-term rate (e.g., 21% US federal + state)
Compute UFCF each year

Step 3: Discount Rate – WACC
$$\text{WACC} = \left( \frac{E}{V} \times r_e \right) + \left( \frac{D}{V} \times r_d \times (1 - T) \right)$$

r_e (Cost of Equity) = Risk-Free Rate + Beta × Equity Risk Premium
Risk-Free: 10Y Treasury yield (~4.0–4.5% in early 2026)
Beta: 5Y weekly vs. market index (often levered → unlever for pure asset beta)
ERP: 4.5–6.0% (Damodaran or Duff & Phelps)

r_d (Cost of Debt): Yield on company bonds or comparable debt + spread
D/E weights: Target capital structure (often current or industry average)
Tax Rate: Marginal (21% US) or effective

Step 4: Terminal Value (Year n+1 onward)
Two dominant methods:
A. Perpetuity Growth Model (Gordon Growth) — most common
$$\text{TV} = \frac{\text{UFCF}_{n+1}}{(\text{WACC} - g)}$$

UFCF_{n+1} = UFCF_n × (1 + g)
g = Perpetual growth rate (long-term GDP + inflation, usually 2.0–3.0%)

B. Exit Multiple Method (common sanity check)
$$\text{TV} = \text{EBITDA}_n \times \text{Exit Multiple}$$

Exit Multiple = Median peer group EV/EBITDA (current or forward)

Blend or triangulate both methods in practice.
Step 5: Discount & Sum to Present Value

Discount each year's UFCF and the Terminal Value:

$$\text{PV of UFCF}_t = \frac{\text{UFCF}_t}{(1 + \text{WACC})^t}$$
$$\text{Enterprise Value} = \sum_{t=1}^{n} \text{PV of UFCF}_t + \frac{\text{TV}}{(1 + \text{WACC})^n}$$
Step 6: Bridge to Equity Value & Per-Share Value
$$\text{Equity Value} = \text{Enterprise Value} + \text{Cash \& Equivalents} - \text{Total Debt} - \text{Minority Interest} - \text{Preferred Stock}$$
$$\text{Equity Value per Share} = \frac{\text{Equity Value}}{\text{Diluted Shares Outstanding}}$$
Sensitivity & Scenario Analysis (Critical in M&A)

Football Field — Vary WACC (±0.5–1.0%) and terminal growth (±0.25–0.50%)
Sensitivity Tables — WACC vs. growth rate, exit multiple vs. growth
Monte Carlo (advanced) — randomize growth, margins, WACC → probability distribution of value

Typical Assumptions in Mid-2026 M&A Deals

Forecast period: 5–7 years (longer for infrastructure/tech)
Terminal growth: 2.0–3.0% (rarely > long-term GDP)
WACC: 8–12% (higher for emerging markets or riskier targets)
Tax rate: 21–25% (US), 19–25% (Europe)
Exit multiple: Current peer median or slight discount for control premium

Common Pitfalls to Avoid

Over-optimistic growth/margins → use conservative base + downside case
Circular WACC (target capital structure vs. current)
Terminal value > 70% of EV → extend forecast or lower g
Mixing levered/unlevered cash flows
Ignoring non-operating assets/liabilities

Real-World M&A Usage

Buy-side: Primary valuation method for strategic buyers and PE (control premium justification)
Sell-side: Fairness opinion component
Negotiation: DCF range often anchors bid/ask spread
Synergies: Run separate DCF with cost/revenue synergies phased in

