3. How to adjust comps for private company in M&A
When using public comps to value a private target, apply these standard adjustments (in order):

Illiquidity / Marketability Discount (DLOM)
Private shares cannot be sold quickly → 10–35% discount on public multiples
Typical range: 15–25% for mid-market private firms
Higher for: small size, no ready buyers, restricted shares
Lower for: strong growth, strategic buyer interest, imminent IPO/liquidity event

Size / Scale Discount
Private companies are usually smaller → 5–20% discount
Reason: less diversification, higher risk, limited access to capital
Often overlaps with DLOM — total combined adjustment frequently 20–40%

Control Premium / Minority Discount
Buy-side M&A (acquiring control): Add 20–40% control premium to public minority multiples
Minority stake valuation: Apply minority discount (10–30%)
In most M&A deals (full acquisition), use control-level multiples → public comps + premium

Growth & Profitability Adjustment
If private company has superior growth/margins → premium (5–20%)
If slower/lower quality → discount (5–15%)

Other Adjustments
Key person / owner dependence → 10–25% discount
Customer/supplier concentration → 5–15% discount
Geographic risk, regulatory exposure → case-by-case


Practical Adjustment Formula (Common in M&A)
textCopyAdjusted Multiple = Public Median Multiple × (1 - DLOM) × (1 - Size Discount) × (1 + Growth Premium) × (1 + Control Premium)
Example (mid-market private SaaS target):

Public SaaS comps median EV/EBITDA = 20×
DLOM 20% → × 0.80 = 16×
Size discount 10% → × 0.90 = 14.4×
Growth premium 10% (faster than peers) → × 1.10 = 15.84×
Control premium 30% (full acquisition) → × 1.30 = 20.6× (final applied multiple)

