Adding debt schedule randomization transforms your basic IRR simulation into a more realistic LBO (Leveraged Buyout) model. In M&A/PE contexts, debt financing is often 40–60% of the purchase price, and its terms (amount, interest rate, amortization, prepayments) introduce significant variability that impacts cash flows and returns.
Key Additions Explained

Initial Debt: Randomized as % of EV (e.g., 50% ±10%, typical LBO leverage).
Interest Rate: Base (SOFR/Term SOFR) + spread (randomized, e.g., 4–6% total rate).
Amortization: Straight-line (e.g., 5% annual principal paydown) + mandatory prepayments (excess cash flow % randomized 25–50%).
Cash Flow Impact: Interest expense reduces FCF; principal paydown further reduces available cash.
Randomization: Debt % (triangular), spread (normal), prepay % (beta skewed high).
Output: IRR now reflects net cash to equity holders (after debt service).

This keeps the sim efficient (still ~1–2s for 10k runs) while capturing leverage risk (e.g., higher debt → higher IRR upside but more downside volatility).
