Which one would you like to add next? Or shall we wrap this into a clean LangChain tool + agent call example?Explain OU process mathThe Ornstein-Uhlenbeck (OU) process is a continuous-time stochastic process that is very frequently used in finance to model mean-reverting quantities — such as interest rates (Vasicek, CIR models), commodity prices, volatility (some stochastic vol models), spreads, and in our case: synergy realization levels after an M&A transaction.
Below is a clear, step-by-step mathematical explanation.
1. Stochastic Differential Equation (SDE)
The OU process is defined by the following SDE:
$$dX_t = \kappa (\theta - X_t) \, dt + \sigma \, dW_t$$
Where:

$  X_t  $          = value of the process at time $  t  $ (e.g., current synergy level in $M)
$  \kappa > 0  $   = speed of mean reversion (how quickly the process returns to the long-term mean)
$  \theta  $       = long-term mean (equilibrium level that $  X_t  $ reverts toward)
$  \sigma > 0  $   = volatility (scale of random shocks)
$  dW_t  $         = increment of a standard Wiener process (Brownian motion) → normally distributed $  N(0, dt)  $

Intuitive meaning:

The drift term $  \kappa (\theta - X_t)  $ pulls $  X_t  $ back toward $  \theta  $ — stronger pull when farther away.
The diffusion term $  \sigma dW_t  $ adds random noise.

2. Solution of the SDE (Exact Expression)
The OU process has a closed-form solution (unlike many other SDEs).
Given initial value $  X_0  $ at time 0, the value at time $  t  $ is:
$$X_t = \theta + (X_0 - \theta) e^{-\kappa t} + \sigma \int_0^t e^{-\kappa (t-s)} \, dW_s$$
The integral part is normally distributed, so $  X_t  $ is conditionally normal:
X_t \,\middle|\, X_0 \sim \mathcal{N}\left(
\theta + (X_0 - \theta) e^{-\kappa t},\;
\frac{\sigma^2}{2\kappa} \left(1 - e^{-2\kappa t}\right)
\right)
This is the most important formula when simulating discrete paths.
3. Discretized Simulation (Euler–Maruyama)
In practice we almost always simulate on a discrete time grid $  t_0, t_1, \dots, t_n  $ with step size $  \Delta t = t_{i+1} - t_i  $.
The simplest (and most common) discretization is Euler–Maruyama:
$$X_{t+\Delta t} = X_t + \kappa (\theta - X_t) \Delta t + \sigma \sqrt{\Delta t} \, Z$$
where $  Z \sim \mathcal{N}(0,1)  $ (standard normal random variable).
Better (exact) discretization — use the conditional normal distribution directly:
$$X_{t+\Delta t} = \theta + (X_t - \theta) e^{-\kappa \Delta t} + \sigma \sqrt{\frac{1 - e^{-2\kappa \Delta t}}{2\kappa}} \, Z$$
This is numerically stable, especially when $  \kappa \Delta t  $ is large.
4. Stationary (Long-Run) Distribution
As $  t \to \infty  $, the process forgets its starting point and converges to a stationary normal distribution:
$$X_\infty \sim \mathcal{N}\left( \theta, \frac{\sigma^2}{2\kappa} \right)$$
Variance = $  \sigma^2 / (2\kappa)  $ → higher reversion speed or lower volatility reduces long-term spread.
5. Half-life of mean reversion
A useful intuitive measure:
$$\text{Half-life} = \frac{\ln(2)}{\kappa}$$

$  \kappa = 1  $ → half-life ≈ 0.69 years (fast reversion)
$  \kappa = 0.5  $ → half-life ≈ 1.39 years (typical for many financial series)
$  \kappa = 0.2  $ → half-life ≈ 3.47 years (slow reversion, e.g. some commodity prices)

In M&A synergy modeling, half-life of 1–2.5 years is realistic (early wins fade over 2–3 years).
