Let me know which one to add next!OU process in interest ratesThe Ornstein–Uhlenbeck (OU) process is one of the most important and widely used stochastic models for interest rates in quantitative finance, especially in the context of short-rate models.
1. Why OU is used for interest rates
Interest rates exhibit mean reversion in the real world:

When rates are very high → central banks usually tighten policy → rates tend to fall back
When rates are very low (even negative) → monetary policy eventually normalizes → rates tend to rise back toward a long-run level

The OU process captures exactly this behavior in continuous time.
2. The Vasicek model – the classic OU interest rate model
The Vasicek model (1977) is simply an OU process applied to the instantaneous short rate $  r_t  $:
$$dr_t = \kappa (\theta - r_t) \, dt + \sigma \, dW_t$$
Where:

$  r_t  $           = instantaneous short rate at time $  t  $
$  \kappa > 0  $    = speed of mean reversion
$  \theta  $        = long-run equilibrium (mean) interest rate
$  \sigma > 0  $    = instantaneous volatility of the short rate
$  dW_t  $         = Wiener process (standard Brownian motion)

This is mathematically identical to the general OU process we discussed earlier, just with $  X_t \equiv r_t  $.
3. Key closed-form results in Vasicek (very powerful)
Because it is an OU process, Vasicek has closed-form solutions for almost everything needed in fixed income:
A. Zero-coupon bond price $  P(t,T)  $ (price at time t of a bond maturing at T)
$$P(t,T) = \exp\left( A(t,T) - B(t,T) r_t \right)$$
Where
$$B(t,T) = \frac{1 - e^{-\kappa (T-t)}}{\kappa}$$
$$A(t,T) = (B(t,T) - (T-t)) \left( \theta - \frac{\sigma^2}{2\kappa^2} \right) - \frac{\sigma^2}{4\kappa} B(t,T)^2$$
B. Yield to maturity
$$Y(t,T) = -\frac{1}{T-t} \ln P(t,T) = \frac{-A(t,T) + B(t,T) r_t}{T-t}$$
C. Bond option prices (e.g. caplets, floorlets, swaptions) — also closed-form via Jamshidian decomposition
D. Stationary distribution (long-run)
$$r_\infty \sim \mathcal{N}\left( \theta,\ \frac{\sigma^2}{2\kappa} \right)$$
4. Main advantages of Vasicek / OU for interest rates

Mean reversion → prevents rates from exploding or going to ±∞
Closed-form bond prices and options → very fast calibration and pricing
Easy to simulate paths (exact discretization available)
Analytical tractability → used as building block for more complex models

